7 An Act relating to state government; amending 74 O.S.
2021, Section 150.12A-1, which relates to the Office
8 of Missing and Murdered Indigenous Persons; deleting
federal funding and grant requirements; and providing
9 an effective date.
10
11
12 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
13 SECTION 1. AMENDATORY 74 O.S. 2021, Section 150.12A-1,
14 is amended to read as follows:
15 Section 150.12A-1. A. The Oklahoma State Bureau of
16 Investigation shall coordinate with the United States Attorney's
17 Office and the United States Department of Justice to obtain federal
18 funding by January 1, 2022, to coordinate efforts and gather data to
19 address the issue of missing and murdered indigenous persons in the
20 State of Oklahoma. The Bureau shall seek and apply for any
21 applicable federal grants and may coordinate with private entities
22 to obtain funding or fulfill grant requirements.
23 B. Upon securing federal funding, the The Bureau shall create
24 an Office of Liaison for Missing and Murdered Indigenous Persons.
ENGR. H. B. NO. 1137 Page 1
1 Any individual hired within the Office shall have significant
2 experience working with tribal communities. Subject to available
3 funding, the Office shall include a missing persons specialist.
4 C. The Office of Liaison for Missing and Murdered Indigenous
5 Persons shall:
6 1. Work with state, tribal and federal law enforcement agencies
7 on missing persons and homicide cases involving American Indian
8 individuals;
9 2. Develop a best practices protocol for law enforcement
10 response to missing persons reports involving American Indian
11 individuals;
12 3. Assist families, tribal agencies and nongovernmental
13 entities in using the National Missing and Unidentified Persons
14 System (NamUs) and other resources;
15 4. Provide guidance to victims' families with navigating state
16 and federal district court cases;
17 5. Coordinate with other state offices including, but not
18 limited to, the Office of the Chief Medical Examiner, agency tribal
19 liaisons and the Secretary of Native American Affairs to develop
20 training and education on missing and murdered indigenous persons
21 issues and the state-tribal government-to-government relationship;
22 6. Facilitate trainings for law enforcement and members of the
23 public on issues relating to missing and murdered indigenous
24 persons; and
ENGR. H. B. NO. 1137 Page 2
1 7. Consult with community organizations that serve indigenous
2 populations to promote community relations and develop best
3 practices.
4 SECTION 2. This act shall become effective November 1, 2025.
5 Passed the House of Representatives the 13th day of March, 2025.
